PALETTE = "Spectral"


def umap_embeddings_viewer(
    df: pd.DataFrame,
    labels: pd.Series,
    n_components: int = 2,
    n_neighbors: int | List[int] = [15],
    supervised: bool = False,
) -> pd.DataFrame:
    """Perform feature dimensional reduction with UMAP and display the results"""

    def umap_model(n_components: int = 2, n_neighbors: int = 15):
        """Instantiate UMAP with default parameters"""
        return UMAP(
            n_neighbors=n_neighbors,
            n_components=n_components,
            metric="cosine",
            densmap=True,
        )

    if isinstance(n_neighbors, int):
        n_neighbors = [n_neighbors]

    dims = [f"Dim{i}" for i in range(1, n_components + 1)]
    X = df.to_numpy()
    dimred = []
    for n in n_neighbors:
        if supervised:
            model = umap_model(n_components, n).fit(X, y=labels.factorize()[0])
        else:
            model = umap_model(n_components, n).fit(X)
        df_dimred = pd.DataFrame(model.embedding_, columns=dims, index=df.index)
        df_dimred["label"] = labels
        df_dimred["neighbors"] = n

        dimred.append(df_dimred)

    df_dimred = pd.concat(dimred, axis=0)

    if n_components == 2:
        if len(n_neighbors) > 1:
            sns.relplot(
                data=df_dimred,
                x="Dim1",
                y="Dim2",
                col="neighbors",
                col_wrap=2,
                hue="label",
                hue_order=sorted(labels.unique()),
                kind="scatter",
                palette=PALETTE,
                facet_kws={"sharex": False, "sharey": False},
            )
        else:
            sns.scatterplot(
                data=df_dimred,
                x="Dim1",
                y="Dim2",
                hue="label",
                hue_order=sorted(labels.unique()),
                palette=PALETTE,
            )
    elif n_components == 3:
        for n in n_neighbors:
            p = sns.pairplot(
                df_dimred.query(f"neighbors == {n}").drop("neighbors", axis=1),
                hue="label",
                hue_order=sorted(labels.unique()),
                palette=PALETTE,
                aspect=2,
            )
            p.fig.suptitle(f"Number of Neighbors: {n}", y=1.08)
    else:
        raise ValueError(
            "Only 2 or 3 number of components (dimension) can be displayed."
        )
    plt.show()
    return df_dimred


def user_labels(df: pd.DataFrame, std_lim: int = 1000):
    """Hierarchical classification based on geo-location heuristic rules"""

    if df["n_clusters"] == 0:
        if df["std_utm"] >= std_lim:
            return "sparse narrow"
        else:
            return "sparse wide"
    elif df["n_clusters"] == 1:
        if df["std_utm"] >= std_lim:
            return "aggregated wide"
        else:
            return "aggregated narrow"
    elif df["n_clusters"] > 1:
        return "multi-aggregation"
    else:
        return "sporadic"


def viz_users_stats(df: pd.DataFrame, ticker_moltip: Optional[int] = None):
    """Display report counts given the classification labels"""

    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 1, figsize=(12, 5), sharex=True)
    df_perc = (df.div(df.sum(axis=1), axis=0) * 100).fillna(0)

    df.index = df.index.astype(str)
    df_perc.index = df_perc.index.astype(str)
    df.plot(kind="bar", cmap=PALETTE, width=1, stacked=True, ax=ax[0])
    df_perc.plot(
        kind="bar", rot=30, cmap=PALETTE, width=1, stacked=True, ax=ax[1], legend=False
    )

    if ticker_moltip is not None:
        ax[1].xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MultipleLocator(ticker_moltip))

Now we apply dimensional reduction and unsupervised clustering to get clusters of users which behavior depends on geo-location and participation quality. We drop the 'sporadic' users from the analysis. Take in account of the following: correlation is present between quality measures, counts present power distributions, n_clusters is discrete while std_utm is continuous

        n_components=2,
        n_neighbors=n_neighbors,
        supervised=False,
    )
    dimred[name] = (Xft, Xft_dimred)

After deciding the optimal hyperparameters, perform clustering with MAP and HDBSCAN. Remember that HDBSCAN assign '-1' label to items that do not belong to any category. Moreover, we use DensMAP with cosine similarity in order to take account of the density distribution and reduce make reduction scale invariant.

In [ ]:
min_samples = 50
n_neighbors = 30
Xft = dimred["scaler"][0]
Xft_dimred = dimred["scaler"][1].query("neighbors == @n_neighbors").iloc[:, :-2]

labels_dimred_cluster = HDBSCAN(
    min_samples=min_samples,
).fit_predict(Xft_dimred)
score = silhouette_score(Xft_dimred, labels_dimred_cluster)
p = sns.scatterplot(
    data=Xft_dimred, x="Dim1", y="Dim2", hue=labels_dimred_cluster, palette=PALETTE
)
p.set_title(f"Silhouette score: {score:.2f}")

Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Silhouette score: 0.45')

Just for comparison, we repeat the clustering but without dimensional reduction. They reach quite a similar result, but MAP seems to provide one additional cluster. Remember that UMAP is generally used for visualization and it was not primarily intended for clustering: only in cases with high-dimensions it's useful for efficiency reasons. If we compute the Silhouette score over Xft its value is lower then the case of feature reduction.

In order to interpret the results, it is necessary to provide a meaningful description of the ML-labels. It seems that user-type-4 grows in importance after EU scale-up of the system, while user-type-1 decrease its participation.

Future Directions¶

  1. Reduce the number of features by aggregation: n_reports/n_points, geometric

mean of quality_target and quality_reports (like F1score), etc 2. Discretize continuous values and apply manhattan distance 3. Improve the heuristic rules by incorporating quality measures
